      • findQS

        public Expressions.SimpleSentence<LogicalOps.LogicalOr,LogicalOps.LogicalAnd> findQS(Expressions.SimpleSentence<LogicalOps.LogicalAnd,LogicalOps.LogicalOr> hypothesis)
        HKL2000 only defines a quasi-support discovery method for a hypothesis that's a clause but that is enough (HKL2000, p28). Because we can use Theorem 2.1 property (3) which is (HKL2000, p17): QS_A(h_1 \wedge h_2, \xi) = QS_A(h_1, \xi) \cap QS_A(h_2, \xi) This means when we have a CNF as a hypothesis, we'll divide it into its component clauses, compute the QS for each of them individually, and get their intersection to get the resulting QA for the CNF.
        Specified by:
        findQS in interface SymbolicResolver
        Parameters:
        hclause - The hypothesis which is a CNF.
        Returns:
        The quasi-support for the hypothesis.

      • findQS

        public Expressions.SimpleSentence<LogicalOps.LogicalOr,LogicalOps.LogicalAnd> findQS(Expressions.Expression<LogicalOps.LogicalOr> hclause)
        QS(h, \xi)= \{ \alpha \in \mathcal{C}_A: \alpha \wedge \xi \models h \} where \alpha is a term, \xi and h are propositional sentences representing the knowledge base and the hypothesis respectively. ref: HKL2000 Theorem 2.7 p24, and then also p28. See the functions computeNegatedPrimeImplicatesSubsetOfD_A and computeSigmaH for how the above formulation is evaluated in this function. This is needed as a public function since it's not possible to pass an empty clause otherwise (needed for finding the QS for inconsistent scenarios.)
        Specified by:
        findQS in interface SymbolicResolver
        Parameters:
        hclause - The hypothesis which is a clause.
        Returns:
        The \Sigma_H for the hypothesis.
